  "prompt": "How does HDMI over Fiber work?",
  "response": "HDMI over Fiber is a technology that allows high-definition video and audio signals to be transmitted over long distances using fiber optic cables. Here's how it works:\n\n1. Signal Conversion\n- HDMI signal is converted from electrical to optical signals\n- Transmitter converts electrical HDMI data into light pulses\n- Fiber optic cable carries light signals instead of electrical signals\n\n2. Fiber Optic Cable Characteristics\n- Uses thin glass or plastic fiber strands\n- Transmits data using light\n- Allows much longer transmission distances than traditional copper cables\n- Immune to electromagnetic interference\n\n3. Key Components\n- Transmitter (HDMI electrical to optical conversion)\n- Fiber optic cable\n- Receiver (optical back to electrical HDMI conversion)\n\n4. Advantages\n- Can transmit signals over distances up to 10 kilometers\n- Supports high-bandwidth 4K and 8K video signals\n- Superior signal quality\n- No signal degradation\n- Low latency\n- Lightweight and flexible cabling\n\n5. Typical Applications\n- Professional AV installations\n- Live event broadcasting\n- Digital signage\n- Large conference centers\n- Medical imaging\n- Broadcasting studios\n\nThe technology enables high-quality, long-distance HDMI signal transmission using light-based communication.",
